1 the power to hold elected officials accountable for their actions and decisions; and
2 WHEREAS, in recognition of its commitment to the principles of transparency and accountability, the
3 Montana Legislature has had a long-standing policy of allowing public access to the information collected in
4 legislative bill drafting files; and
5 WHEREAS, restoring and maintaining public access to bill drafting files will encourage the public's
6 assertion of the right to know and facilitate more meaningful participation under the right of participation in the
7 legislative process; and
8 WHEREAS, the Speech or Debate clause in Article V, section 8, of the Montana Constitution states
9 that a legislator "shall not be questioned in any other place for any speech or debate in the legislature"; and
10 WHEREAS, providing access to the public to a bill drafting file in furtherance of the right to know and
11 the right of participation as protected in the Montana Constitution does not in and of itself involve questioning a
12 legislator's speech or debate; and
13 WHEREAS, the Speech or Debate clause provides a legislator the privilege from having records or
14 communications regarding legitimate legislative acts used against the legislator, but the clause does not create
15 a privilege in the disclosure of the legislator's communications to another person, and therefore the materials
16 disclosed in a bill drafting file may not be used to prosecute a legislator, either criminally or civilly, for the
17 legislator's legitimate legislative acts; and
18 WHEREAS, no other privilege can exist to protect communications between a legislator and a bill
19 drafter because legal privileges are waived when the privilege-holder voluntarily discloses the privileged
20 information to another person, including a bill drafter, and because the bill drafter is a third party employed by
21 the Legislative Branch and not employed by the individual legislator; and
22 WHEREAS, bill drafting files often contain communications between a bill drafter and parties that are
23 not legislators, which are clearly not protected from disclosure under the Montana Constitution, whether or not a
24 legislator is included in the communications; and
25 WHEREAS, the heart of the Speech or Debate clause is to protect a legislator's legitimate legislative
26 acts from undue prosecution or harassment from either the Executive Branch or the Judicial Branch of
27 government, with which the Legislative Branch is a co-equal branch of government; and
28 WHEREAS, the Legislature deems it appropriate to strike a balance between the public's right to know
