1 person, or preserved in the legislative bill drafting file.
2 (c) A legislator is entitled to assert legislative privilege to prohibit disclosure of writings or
3 documents that are kept private by the legislator and not shared with another person. A legislator waives that
4 privilege if the legislator voluntarily provides the writings or documents related to a bill drafting file to another
5 person.
6 (d) A legislator is entitled to assert legislative privilege to prohibit disclosure of communications or
7 documents that are exchanged between the legislator and the legislator's personal staff when the legislator has
8 an expectation of privacy. A legislator waives that privilege if the legislator voluntarily provides communications
9 or documents related to a bill drafting file to a third party.
10 (e) Legislative privilege does not apply to communications between a legislator and chamber staff
11 or legislative branch staff and does not prevent those communications from being disclosed pursuant to a
12 public records request because the chamber staff and legislative branch staff are employed by the legislature in
13 its entirety and not by an individual legislator.
14 (4) For the purposes of this section, the following definitions apply:
15 (a) "Chamber staff" means the staff of the house of representatives and the staff of the senate as
16 provided for in 5-2-221 and legislative rules.
17 (b) "Legislative branch staff" means the staff of the:
18 (i) legislative services division provided for in 5-11-111;
19 (ii) legislative fiscal division provided for in 5-12-301; and
20 (iii) legislative audit division provided for in 5-13-301.
21 (c) "Personal staff" means a legislative aide employed by an individual legislator and designated
22 pursuant to legislative rules.
23
